# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algebraic-number-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The beginnings of algebraic number theory can be traced to Diophantine equations, named after the 3rd-century Alexandrian mathematician, Diophantus, who studied them and developed methods for the solution of some kinds of Diophantine equations.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Diophantine equations have been studied for thousands of years.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, the solutions to the quadratic Diophantine equation *x*2 + *y*2 = *z*2 are given by the Pythagorean triples, originally solved by the Babylonians (c.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Solutions to linear Diophantine equations, such as 26*x* + 65*y* = 13, may be found using the Euclidean algorithm (c.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Diophantus's major work was the *Arithmetica*, of which only a portion has survived.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Fermat's Last Theorem was first conjectured by Pierre de Fermat in 1637, famously in the margin of a copy of *Arithmetica* where he claimed he had a proof that was too large to fit in the margin.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] No successful proof was published until 1995 despite the efforts of countless mathematicians during the 358 intervening years.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The unsolved problem stimulated the development of algebraic number theory in the 19th century and the proof of the modularity theorem in the 20th century.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] One of the founding works of algebraic number theory, the ***Disquisitiones Arithmeticae*** (Latin: *Arithmetical Investigations*) is a textbook of number theory written in Latin by Carl Friedrich Gauss in 1798 when Gauss was 21 and first published in 1801 when he was 24.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In this book Gauss brings together results in number theory obtained by mathematicians such as Fermat, Euler, Lagrange and Legendre and adds important new results of his own.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Before the *Disquisitiones* was published, number theory consisted of a collection of isolated theorems and conjectures.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Gauss brought the work of his predecessors together with his own original work into a systematic framework, filled in gaps, corrected unsound proofs, and extended the subject in numerous ways.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The *Disquisitiones* was the starting point for the work of other nineteenth century European mathematicians including Ernst Kummer, Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet and Richard Dedekind.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Many of the annotations given by Gauss are in effect announcements of further research of his own, some of which remained unpublished.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] They must have appeared particularly cryptic to his contemporaries; we can now read them as containing the germs of the theories of L-functions and complex multiplication, in particular.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In a couple of papers in 1838 and 1839 Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet proved the first class number formula, for quadratic forms (later refined by his student Leopold Kronecker).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The formula, which Jacobi called a result "touching the utmost of human acumen", opened the way for similar results regarding more general number fields.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Based on his research of the structure of the unit group of quadratic fields, he proved the Dirichlet unit theorem, a fundamental result in algebraic number theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] He first used the pigeonhole principle, a basic counting argument, in the proof of a theorem in diophantine approximation, later named after him Dirichlet's approximation theorem.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] He published important contributions to Fermat's last theorem, for which he proved the cases *n* = 5 and *n* = 14, and to the biquadratic reciprocity law.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The Dirichlet divisor problem, for which he found the first results, is still an unsolved problem in number theory despite later contributions by other researchers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Richard Dedekind's study of Lejeune Dirichlet's work was what led him to his later study of algebraic number fields and ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] 1879 and 1894 editions of the *Vorlesungen* included supplements introducing the notion of an ideal, fundamental to ring theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] (The word "Ring", introduced later by Hilbert, does not appear in Dedekind's work.) Dedekind defined an ideal as a subset of a set of numbers, composed of algebraic integers that satisfy polynomial equations with integer coefficients.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The concept underwent further development in the hands of Hilbert and, especially, of Emmy Noether.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Ideals generalize Ernst Eduard Kummer's ideal numbers, devised as part of Kummer's 1843 attempt to prove Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] David Hilbert unified the field of algebraic number theory with his 1897 treatise *Zahlbericht* (literally "report on numbers").
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] He also resolved a significant number-theory problem formulated by Waring in 1770.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] As with the finiteness theorem, he used an existence proof that shows there must be solutions for the problem rather than providing a mechanism to produce the answers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] He then had little more to publish on the subject; but the emergence of Hilbert modular forms in the dissertation of a student means his name is further attached to a major area.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] He made a series of conjectures on class field theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The concepts were highly influential, and his own contribution lives on in the names of the Hilbert class field and of the Hilbert symbol of local class field theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Results were mostly proved by 1930, after work by Teiji Takagi.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Emil Artin established the Artin reciprocity law in a series of papers (1924; 1927; 1930).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This law is a general theorem in number theory that forms a central part of global class field theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The term "reciprocity law" refers to a long line of more concrete number theoretic statements which it generalized, from the quadratic reciprocity law and the reciprocity laws of Eisenstein and Kummer to Hilbert's product formula for the norm symbol.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Artin's result provided a partial solution to Hilbert's ninth problem.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Around 1955, Japanese mathematicians Goro Shimura and Yutaka Taniyama observed a possible link between two apparently completely distinct, branches of mathematics, elliptic curves and modular forms.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The resulting modularity theorem (at the time known as the Taniyama–Shimura conjecture) states that every elliptic curve is modular, meaning that it can be associated with a unique modular form.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] It was initially dismissed as unlikely or highly speculative, but was taken more seriously when number theorist André Weil found evidence supporting it, yet no proof; as a result the "astounding" conjecture was often known as the Taniyama–Shimura-Weil conjecture.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] It became a part of the Langlands program, a list of important conjectures needing proof or disproof.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] From 1993 to 1994, Andrew Wiles provided a proof of the modularity theorem for semistable elliptic curves, which, together with Ribet's theorem, provided a proof for Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Almost every mathematician at the time had previously considered both Fermat's Last Theorem and the Modularity Theorem either impossible or virtually impossible to prove, even given the most cutting-edge developments.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Wiles first announced his proof in June 1993 in a version that was soon recognized as having a serious gap at a key point.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The proof was corrected by Wiles, partly in collaboration with Richard Taylor, and the final, widely accepted version was released in September 1994, and formally published in 1995.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The proof uses many techniques from algebraic geometry and number theory, and has many ramifications in these branches of mathematics.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] It also uses standard constructions of modern algebraic geometry, such as the category of schemes and Iwasawa theory, and other 20th-century techniques not available to Fermat.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] An important property of the ring of rational integers **Z** is that it satisfies the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, that every (positive) integer has a factorization into a product of prime numbers, and this factorization is unique up to the ordering of the factors.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This may no longer be true in the ring of integers *O* of an algebraic number field *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For *O* and commutative rings in general, a prime element is an element of the ring satisfying the key property of prime numbers given by Euclid's lemma: a *prime element* is an element *p* of *O* such that if *p* divides a product *ab*, then it divides one of the factors *a* or *b*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This property is closely related to primality in the integers, because any positive integer satisfying this property is either 1 or a prime number.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, −2 is not a prime number because it is negative, but it is a prime element.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In general, if *u* is a unit, meaning a number with a multiplicative inverse in *O*, and if *p* is a prime element, then *up* is also a prime element.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Numbers such as *p* and *up* are said to be *associate*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In the integers, the primes *p* and −*p* are associate, but only one of these is positive.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Requiring that prime numbers be positive selects a unique element from among a set of associated prime elements.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] When *K* is not the rational numbers, however, there is no analog of positivity.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, in the Gaussian integers **Z**[*i*], the numbers 1 + 2*i* and −2 + *i* are associate because the latter is the product of the former by *i*, but there is no way to single out one as being more canonical than the other.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] which prove that in **Z**[*i*], it is not true that factorizations are unique up to the order of the factors.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For this reason, one adopts the definition of unique factorization used in unique factorization domains (UFDs).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In a UFD, the prime elements occurring in a factorization are only expected to be unique up to units and their ordering.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] However, even with this weaker definition, many rings of integers in algebraic number fields do not admit unique factorization.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] There is an algebraic obstruction called the ideal class group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] When the ideal class group is trivial, the ring is a UFD.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] When it is not, there is a distinction between a prime element and an irreducible element.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] An *irreducible element* *x* is an element such that if *x* = *yz*, then either *y* or *z* is a unit.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] These are the elements that cannot be factored any further.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Every element in *O* admits a factorization into irreducible elements, but it may admit more than one.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This is because, while all prime elements are irreducible, some irreducible elements may not be prime.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, consider the ring **Z**[√-5].
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In this ring, the numbers 3, 2 + √-5 and 2 - √-5 are irreducible.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This equation shows that 3 divides the product (2 + √-5)(2 - √-5) = 9.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] If 3 were a prime element, then it would divide 2 + √-5 or 2 - √-5, but it does not, because all elements divisible by 3 are of the form 3*a* + 3*b*√-5.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Similarly, 2 + √-5 and 2 - √-5 divide the product 32, but neither of these elements divides 3 itself, so neither of them are prime.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] As there is no sense in which the elements 3, 2 + √-5 and 2 - √-5 can be made equivalent, unique factorization fails in **Z**[√-5].
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Unlike the situation with units, where uniqueness could be repaired by weakening the definition, overcoming this failure requires a new perspective.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] where each ${\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ is a prime ideal, and where this expression is unique up to the order of the factors.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In particular, this is true if *I* is the principal ideal generated by a single element.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This is the strongest sense in which the ring of integers of a general number field admits unique factorization.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In the language of ring theory, it says that rings of integers are Dedekind domains.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] When *O* is a UFD, every prime ideal is generated by a prime element.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Otherwise, there are prime ideals which are not generated by prime elements.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In **Z**[√-5], for instance, the ideal (2, 1 + √-5) is a prime ideal which cannot be generated by a single element.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Historically, the idea of factoring ideals into prime ideals was preceded by Ernst Kummer's introduction of ideal numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] These are numbers lying in an extension field *E* of *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This extension field is now known as the Hilbert class field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] By the principal ideal theorem, every prime ideal of *O* generates a principal ideal of the ring of integers of *E*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] A generator of this principal ideal is called an ideal number.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Kummer used these as a substitute for the failure of unique factorization in cyclotomic fields.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] These eventually led Richard Dedekind to introduce a forerunner of ideals and to prove unique factorization of ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] An ideal which is prime in the ring of integers in one number field may fail to be prime when extended to a larger number field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Consider, for example, the prime numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The corresponding ideals *p***Z** are prime ideals of the ring **Z**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] However, when this ideal is extended to the Gaussian integers to obtain *p***Z**[*i*], it may or may not be prime.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] note that because 1 + *i* = (1 − *i*) ⋅ *i*, the ideals generated by 1 + *i* and 1 − *i* are the same.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] A complete answer to the question of which ideals remain prime in the Gaussian integers is provided by Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] It implies that for an odd prime number *p*, *p***Z**[*i*] is a prime ideal if *p* ≡ 3 (mod 4) and is not a prime ideal if *p* ≡ 1 (mod 4).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This, together with the observation that the ideal (1 + *i*)**Z**[*i*] is prime, provides a complete description of the prime ideals in the Gaussian integers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Generalizing this simple result to more general rings of integers is a basic problem in algebraic number theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Class field theory accomplishes this goal when *K* is an abelian extension of **Q** (that is, a Galois extension with abelian Galois group).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Unique factorization fails in *O* if and only if there are prime ideals that fail to be principal.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The object which measures the failure of prime ideals to be principal is called the ideal class group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Defining the ideal class group requires enlarging the set of ideals in a ring of algebraic integers so that they admit a group structure.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This is done by generalizing ideals to fractional ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] A fractional ideal is an additive subgroup *J* of *K* which is closed under multiplication by elements of *O*, meaning that *xJ* ⊆ *J* if *x* ∈ *O*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] All ideals of *O* are also fractional ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] If *I* and *J* are fractional ideals, then the set *IJ* of all products of an element in *I* and an element in *J* is also a fractional ideal.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This operation makes the set of non-zero fractional ideals into a group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The principal fractional ideals, meaning the ones of the form *Ox* where *x* ∈ *K*×, form a subgroup of the group of all non-zero fractional ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The quotient of the group of non-zero fractional ideals by this subgroup is the ideal class group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Two fractional ideals *I* and *J* represent the same element of the ideal class group if and only if there exists an element *x* ∈ *K* such that *xI* = *J*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Therefore, the ideal class group makes two fractional ideals equivalent if one is as close to being principal as the other is.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The ideal class group is generally denoted Cl *K*, Cl *O*, or Pic *O* (with the last notation identifying it with the Picard group in algebraic geometry).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The number of elements in the class group is called the **class number** of *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This means that there are only two ideal classes, the class of principal fractional ideals, and the class of a non-principal fractional ideal such as (2, 1 + √-5).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The ideal class group has another description in terms of divisors.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] These are formal objects which represent possible factorizations of numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The divisor group Div *K* is defined to be the free abelian group generated by the prime ideals of *O*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] There is a group homomorphism from *K*×, the non-zero elements of *K* up to multiplication, to Div *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The kernel of div is the group of units in *O*, while the cokernel is the ideal class group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Some number fields, such as **Q**(√2), can be specified as subfields of the real numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Abstractly, such a specification corresponds to a field homomorphism *K* → **R** or *K* → **C**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] These are called **real embeddings** and **complex embeddings**, respectively.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] A real quadratic field **Q**(√*a*), with *a* ∈ **Z**, *a* > 0, and *a* not a perfect square, is so-called because it admits two real embeddings but no complex embeddings.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] These are the field homomorphisms which send √*a* to √*a* and to −√*a*, respectively.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Dually, an imaginary quadratic field **Q**(√−*a*) admits no real embeddings but admits a conjugate pair of complex embeddings.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] One of these embeddings sends √−*a* to √−*a*, while the other sends it to its complex conjugate, −√−*a*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Conventionally, the number of real embeddings of *K* is denoted *r*1, while the number of conjugate pairs of complex embeddings is denoted *r*2.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] It is a theorem that *r*1 + 2*r*2 = *d*, where *d* is the degree of *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Considering all embeddings at once determines a function $M\colon K\to \mathbf {R} ^{r_{1}}\oplus \mathbf {C} ^{r_{2}}$ , or equivalently $M\colon K\to \mathbf {R} ^{r_{1}}\oplus \mathbf {R} ^{2r_{2}}.$ This is called the **Minkowski embedding**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The subspace of the codomain fixed by complex conjugation is a real vector space of dimension *d* called Minkowski space.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Because the Minkowski embedding is defined by field homomorphisms, multiplication of elements of *K* by an element *x* ∈ *K* corresponds to multiplication by a diagonal matrix in the Minkowski embedding.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The dot product on Minkowski space corresponds to the trace form $\langle x,y\rangle =\operatorname {Tr} (xy)$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The image of *O* under the Minkowski embedding is a *d*-dimensional lattice.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] If *B* is a basis for this lattice, then det *B*T*B* is the **discriminant** of *O*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The covolume of the image of *O* is ${\sqrt {|\Delta |}}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Real and complex embeddings can be put on the same footing as prime ideals by adopting a perspective based on valuations.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In addition to the usual absolute value function |·| : **Q** → **R**, there are p-adic absolute value functions |·|*p* : **Q** → **R**, defined for each prime number *p*, which measure divisibility by *p*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Ostrowski's theorem states that these are all possible absolute value functions on **Q** (up to equivalence).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Therefore, absolute values are a common language to describe both the real embedding of **Q** and the prime numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] A **place** of an algebraic number field is an equivalence class of absolute value functions on *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] There is a ${\mathfrak {p}}$ -adic absolute value for each prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}$ of *O*, and, like the *p*-adic absolute values, it measures divisibility.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The other type of place is specified using a real or complex embedding of *K* and the standard absolute value function on **R** or **C**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Because absolute values are unable to distinguish between a complex embedding and its conjugate, a complex embedding and its conjugate determine the same place.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Therefore, there are *r*1 real places and *r*2 complex places.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Because places encompass the primes, places are sometimes referred to as **primes**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] When this is done, finite places are called **finite primes** and infinite places are called **infinite primes**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] If *v* is a valuation corresponding to an absolute value, then one frequently writes $v\mid \infty$ to mean that *v* is an infinite place and $v\nmid \infty$ to mean that it is a finite place.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Considering all the places of the field together produces the adele ring of the number field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The adele ring allows one to simultaneously track all the data available using absolute values.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This produces significant advantages in situations where the behavior at one place can affect the behavior at other places, as in the Artin reciprocity law.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] There is a geometric analogy for places at infinity which holds on the function fields of curves.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, let $k=\mathbb {F} _{q}$ and $X/k$ be a smooth, projective, algebraic curve.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The function field $F=k(X)$ has many absolute values, or places, and each corresponds to a point on the curve.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] If X is the projective completion of an affine curve ${\hat {X}}\subset \mathbb {A} ^{n}$ then the points in $X-{\hat {X}}$ correspond to the places at infinity.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Then, the completion of F at one of these points gives an analogue of the p -adics.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, if $X=\mathbb {P} ^{1}$ then its function field is isomorphic to $k(t)$ where t is an indeterminant and the field F is the field of fractions of polynomials in t .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Then, a place $v_{p}$ at a point $p\in X$ measures the order of vanishing or the order of a pole of a fraction of polynomials $p(x)/q(x)$ at the point p .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, if $p=[2:1]$ , so on the affine chart $x_{1}\neq 0$ this corresponds to the point $2\in \mathbb {A} ^{1}$ , the valuation $v_{2}$ measures the order of vanishing of $p(x)$ minus the order of vanishing of $q(x)$ at 2 .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The integers have only two units, 1 and −1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Other rings of integers may admit more units.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The Gaussian integers have four units, the previous two as well as ±*i*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The Eisenstein integers **Z**[exp(2π*i* / 3)] have six units.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The integers in real quadratic number fields have infinitely many units.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, in **Z**[√3], every power of 2 + √3 is a unit, and all these powers are distinct.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In general, the group of units of *O*, denoted *O*×, is a finitely generated abelian group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups therefore implies that it is a direct sum of a torsion part and a free part.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Reinterpreting this in the context of a number field, the torsion part consists of the roots of unity that lie in *O*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The free part is described by Dirichlet's unit theorem.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This theorem says that rank of the free part is *r*1 + *r*2 − 1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Thus, for example, the only fields for which the rank of the free part is zero are **Q** and the imaginary quadratic fields.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] A more precise statement giving the structure of *O*× ⊗**Z** **Q** as a Galois module for the Galois group of *K*/**Q** is also possible.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The free part of the unit group can be studied using the infinite places of *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] where *v* varies over the infinite places of *K* and |·|*v* is the absolute value associated with *v*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The function *L* is a homomorphism from *K*× to a real vector space.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] It can be shown that the image of *O*× is a lattice that spans the hyperplane defined by $x_{1}+\cdots +x_{r_{1}+r_{2}}=0.$ The covolume of this lattice is the **regulator** of the number field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] One of the simplifications made possible by working with the adele ring is that there is a single object, the idele class group, that describes both the quotient by this lattice and the ideal class group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The Dedekind zeta function of a number field, analogous to the Riemann zeta function, is an analytic object which describes the behavior of prime ideals in *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] When *K* is an abelian extension of **Q**, Dedekind zeta functions are products of Dirichlet L-functions, with there being one factor for each Dirichlet character.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The trivial character corresponds to the Riemann zeta function.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] When *K* is a Galois extension, the Dedekind zeta function is the Artin L-function of the regular representation of the Galois group of *K*, and it has a factorization in terms of irreducible Artin representations of the Galois group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The zeta function is related to the other invariants described above by the class number formula.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Completing a number field *K* at a place *w* gives a complete field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] If the valuation is Archimedean, one obtains **R** or **C**, if it is non-Archimedean and lies over a prime *p* of the rationals, one obtains a finite extension $K_{w}/\mathbf {Q} _{p}:$ a complete, discrete valued field with finite residue field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This process simplifies the arithmetic of the field and allows the local study of problems.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] For example, the Kronecker–Weber theorem can be deduced easily from the analogous local statement.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The philosophy behind the study of local fields is largely motivated by geometric methods.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In algebraic geometry, it is common to study varieties locally at a point by localizing to a maximal ideal.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Global information can then be recovered by gluing together local data.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This spirit is adopted in algebraic number theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Given a prime in the ring of algebraic integers in a number field, it is desirable to study the field locally at that prime.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Therefore, one localizes the ring of algebraic integers to that prime and then completes the fraction field much in the spirit of geometry.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] One classical result in algebraic number theory is that the ideal class group of an algebraic number field *K* is finite.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] This is a consequence of Minkowski's theorem since there are only finitely many integral ideals with norm less than a fixed positive integer page 78.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The order of the class group is called the class number, and is often denoted by the letter *h*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Dirichlet's unit theorem provides a description of the structure of the multiplicative group of units *O*× of the ring of integers *O*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] In other words, *O*× is a finitely generated abelian group of rank *r*1 + *r*2 − 1 whose torsion consists of the roots of unity in *O*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] A **reciprocity law** is a generalization of the law of quadratic reciprocity.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] There are several different ways to express reciprocity laws.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Hilbert reformulated the reciprocity laws as saying that a product over *p* of Hilbert symbols (*a*,*b*/*p*), taking values in roots of unity, is equal to 1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Artin's reformulated reciprocity law states that the Artin symbol from ideals (or ideles) to elements of a Galois group is trivial on a certain subgroup.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Several more recent generalizations express reciprocity laws using cohomology of groups or representations of adelic groups or algebraic K-groups, and their relationship with the original quadratic reciprocity law can be hard to see.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] The **class number formula** relates many important invariants of a number field to a special value of its Dedekind zeta function.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Algebraic number theory interacts with many other mathematical disciplines.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Via the analogy of function fields vs. number fields, it relies on techniques and ideas from algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Moreover, the study of higher-dimensional schemes over **Z** instead of number rings is referred to as arithmetic geometry.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/algebraic-number-theory] Algebraic number theory is also used in the study of arithmetic hyperbolic 3-manifolds.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In mathematics, a **Dedekind domain** or **Dedekind ring**, named after Richard Dedekind, is an integral domain in which every nonzero proper ideal factors into a product of prime ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] It can be shown that such a factorization is then necessarily unique up to the order of the factors.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] There are at least three other characterizations of Dedekind domains that are sometimes taken as the definition: see below.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] A field is a commutative ring in which there are no nontrivial proper ideals, so that any field is a Dedekind domain, however in a rather vacuous way.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Some authors add the requirement that a Dedekind domain not be a field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Many more authors state theorems for Dedekind domains with the implicit proviso that they may require trivial modifications for the case of fields.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] An immediate consequence of the definition is that every principal ideal domain (PID) is a Dedekind domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In fact a Dedekind domain is a unique factorization domain (UFD) if and only if it is a PID.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In the 19th century it became a common technique to gain insight into integer solutions of polynomial equations using rings of algebraic numbers of higher degree.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] For instance, fix a positive integer m .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In the attempt to determine which integers are represented by the quadratic form $x^{2}+my^{2}$ , it is natural to factor the quadratic form into $(x+{\sqrt {-m}}y)(x-{\sqrt {-m}}y)$ , the factorization taking place in the ring of integers of the quadratic field $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {-m}})$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Similarly, for a positive integer n the polynomial $z^{n}-y^{n}$ (which is relevant for solving the Fermat equation $x^{n}+y^{n}=z^{n}$ ) can be factored over the ring $\mathbb {Z} [\zeta _{n}]$ , where $\zeta _{n}$ is a primitive *n*-th root of unity.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] For a few small values of m and n these rings of algebraic integers are PIDs, and this can be seen as an explanation of the classical successes of Fermat ( $m=1,n=4$ ) and Euler ( $m=2,3,n=3$ ).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] By this time a procedure for determining whether the ring of all algebraic integers of a given quadratic field $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {D}})$ is a PID was well known to the quadratic form theorists.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Especially, Gauss had looked at the case of imaginary quadratic fields: he found exactly nine values of $D<0$ for which the ring of integers is a PID and conjectured that there were no further values.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In 1847 Gabriel Lamé announced a solution of Fermat's Last Theorem for all $n>2$ ; that is, that the Fermat equation has no solutions in nonzero integers, but it turned out that his solution hinged on the assumption that the cyclotomic ring $\mathbb {Z} [\zeta _{n}]$ is a UFD.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Ernst Kummer had shown three years before that this was not the case already for $n=23$ (the full, finite list of values for which $\mathbb {Z} [\zeta _{n}]$ is a UFD is now known).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] At the same time, Kummer developed powerful new methods to prove Fermat's Last Theorem at least for a large class of prime exponents n using what we now recognize as the fact that the ring $\mathbb {Z} [\zeta _{n}]$ is a Dedekind domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In fact Kummer worked not with ideals but with "ideal numbers", and the modern definition of an ideal was given by Dedekind.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] By the 20th century, algebraists and number theorists had come to realize that the condition of being a PID is rather delicate, whereas the condition of being a Dedekind domain is quite robust.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] For instance the ring of ordinary integers is a PID, but as seen above the ring ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ of algebraic integers in a number field K need not be a PID.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In fact, although Gauss also conjectured that there are infinitely many primes p such that the ring of integers of $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {p}})$ is a PID, it is not yet known whether there are infinitely many number fields K (of arbitrary degree) such that ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ is a PID.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] On the other hand, the ring of integers in a number field is always a Dedekind domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Another illustration of the delicate/robust dichotomy is the fact that being a Dedekind domain is, among Noetherian domains, a **local** property: a Noetherian domain R is Dedekind iff for every maximal ideal M of R the localization $R_{M}$ is a Dedekind ring.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] But a local domain is a Dedekind ring iff it is a PID iff it is a discrete valuation ring (DVR), so the same local characterization cannot hold for PIDs: rather, one may say that the concept of a Dedekind ring is the **globalization** of that of a DVR.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Every nonzero proper ideal factors into primes.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] is Noetherian, and the localization at each maximal ideal is a discrete valuation ring.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] one (that is, every nonzero prime ideal is maximal).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] A commutative ring (not necessarily a domain) with unity satisfying this condition is called a containment-division ring (CDR).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Thus a Dedekind domain is a domain that either is a field, or satisfies any one, and hence all five, of (DD1) through (DD5).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Which of these conditions one takes as the definition is therefore merely a matter of taste.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In practice, it is often easiest to verify (DD4).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Any ideal in a Dedekind domain is generated by at most two elements.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In fact, a stronger condition gives another characterization of Dedekind domains: an integral domain R is a Dedekind domain if and only if for any nonzero ideal $I\subset R$ and nonzero $a\in I$ there exists $b\in I$ such that $I=(a,b)$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] A Krull domain is a higher-dimensional analog of a Dedekind domain: a Dedekind domain that is not a field is a Krull domain of dimension 1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] This notion can be used to study the various characterizations of a Dedekind domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In fact, this is the definition of a Dedekind domain used in Bourbaki's "Commutative algebra".
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] A Dedekind domain can also be characterized in terms of homological algebra: an integral domain is a Dedekind domain if and only if it is a hereditary ring; that is, every submodule of a projective module over it is projective.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Similarly, an integral domain is a Dedekind domain if and only if every divisible module over it is injective.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] All principal ideal domains and therefore all discrete valuation rings are Dedekind domains.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] As above, this includes all the examples considered by Kummer and Dedekind and was the motivating case for the general definition, and these remain among the most studied examples.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] The other class of Dedekind rings that is arguably of equal importance comes from geometry: let *C* be a nonsingular geometrically integral *affine* algebraic curve over a field *k*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Then the coordinate ring *k*[*C*] of regular functions on *C* is a Dedekind domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Applying this theorem when *R* is itself a PID gives us a way of building Dedekind domains out of PIDs.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Taking *R* = **Z**, this construction says precisely that rings of integers of number fields are Dedekind domains.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Taking *R* = *k*[*t*], one obtains the above case of nonsingular affine curves as branched coverings of the affine line.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Zariski and Samuel were sufficiently taken with this construction to ask whether every Dedekind domain arises from it; that is, by starting with a PID and taking the integral closure in a finite degree field extension.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] A surprisingly simple negative answer was given by L.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] If the situation is as above but the extension *L* of *K* is algebraic of infinite degree, then it is still possible for the integral closure *S* of *R* in *L* to be a Dedekind domain, but it is not guaranteed.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] For example, take again *R* = **Z**, *K* = **Q** and now take *L* to be the field ${\overline {\textbf {Q}}}$ of all algebraic numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] The integral closure is then the ring ${\overline {\textbf {Z}}}$ of all algebraic integers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Since the square root of an algebraic integer is again an algebraic integer, it is not possible to factor any nonzero nonunit algebraic integer into a finite product of irreducible elements, which implies that ${\overline {\textbf {Z}}}$ is not even Noetherian.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In general, the integral closure of a Dedekind domain in an infinite algebraic extension is a Prüfer domain; it turns out that the ring of algebraic integers is slightly more special than this: it is a Bézout domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Let *R* be an integral domain with fraction field *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Given two fractional ideals *I* and *J*, one defines their product *IJ* as the set of all finite sums $\sum _{n}i_{n}j_{n},\,i_{n}\in I,\,j_{n}\in J$ : the product *IJ* is again a fractional ideal.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] The set Frac(*R*) of all fractional ideals endowed with the above product is a commutative semigroup and in fact a monoid: the identity element is the fractional ideal *R*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] One then tautologically has $I^{*}I\subset R$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In fact one has equality if and only if *I*, as an element of the monoid of Frac(*R*), is invertible.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In other words, if *I* has any inverse, then the inverse must be $I^{*}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] A **principal fractional ideal** is one of the form $xR$ for some nonzero *x* in *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Note that each principal fractional ideal is invertible, the inverse of $xR$ being simply ${\frac {1}{x}}R$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] We denote the subgroup of principal fractional ideals by Prin(*R*).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] A domain *R* is a PID if and only if every fractional ideal is principal.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In this case, we have Frac(*R*) = Prin(*R*) = $K^{\times }/R^{\times }$ , since two principal fractional ideals $xR$ and $yR$ are equal iff $xy^{-1}$ is a unit in *R*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] For a general domain *R*, it is meaningful to take the quotient of the monoid Frac(*R*) of all fractional ideals by the submonoid Prin(*R*) of principal fractional ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] However this quotient itself is generally only a monoid.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In fact it is easy to see that the class of a fractional ideal I in Frac(*R*)/Prin(*R*) is invertible if and only if I itself is invertible.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Now we can appreciate (DD3): in a Dedekind domain (and only in a Dedekind domain) every fractional ideal is invertible.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Thus these are precisely the class of domains for which Frac(*R*)/Prin(*R*) forms a group, the ideal class group Cl(*R*) of *R*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] This group is trivial if and only if *R* is a PID, so can be viewed as quantifying the obstruction to a general Dedekind domain being a PID.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] For an arbitrary domain one may define the Picard group Pic(*R*) as the group of invertible fractional ideals Inv(*R*) modulo the subgroup of principal fractional ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] For a Dedekind domain this is of course the same as the ideal class group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] which is however generally neither injective nor surjective.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] This is an affine analogue of the distinction between Cartier divisors and Weil divisors on a singular algebraic variety.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Claborn asserts that for any abelian group *G* whatsoever, there exists a Dedekind domain *R* whose ideal class group is isomorphic to *G*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Leedham-Green showed that such an *R* may be constructed as the integral closure of a PID in a quadratic field extension.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Rosen showed how to realize any countable abelian group as the class group of a Dedekind domain that is a subring of the rational function field of an elliptic curve, and conjectured that such an "elliptic" construction should be possible for a general abelian group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Rosen's conjecture was proven in 2008 by P.L.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In contrast, one of the basic theorems in algebraic number theory asserts that the class group of the ring of integers of a number field is finite.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Its cardinality is called the class number.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In view of the well known and exceedingly useful structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain (PID), it is natural to ask for a corresponding theory for finitely generated modules over a Dedekind domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Let us briefly recall the structure theory in the case of a finitely generated module M over a PID R .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] We define the torsion submodule T to be the set of elements m of M such that $rm=0$ for some nonzero r in R .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] (M1) T can be decomposed into a direct sum of cyclic torsion modules, each of the form $R/I$ for some nonzero ideal I of R .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] By the Chinese Remainder Theorem, each $R/I$ can further be decomposed into a direct sum of submodules of the form $R/P^{i}$ , where $P^{i}$ is a power of a prime ideal.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] differ only in the order of the factors.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] (M2) The torsion submodule is a direct summand.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] That is, there exists a complementary submodule P of M such that $M=T\oplus P$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] (M3PID) P isomorphic to $R^{n}$ for a uniquely determined non-negative integer n .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In particular, P is a finitely generated free module.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Now let M be a finitely generated module over an arbitrary Dedekind domain R .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] However, it follows from (M3PID) that a finitely generated torsionfree module P over a PID is free.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In particular, it asserts that all fractional ideals are principal, a statement that is false whenever R is not a PID.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In other words, the nontriviality of the class group $Cl(R)$ causes (M3PID) to fail.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Remarkably, the additional structure in torsionfree finitely generated modules over an arbitrary Dedekind domain is precisely controlled by the class group, as we now explain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] (M3DD) P is isomorphic to a direct sum of rank one projective modules: $P\cong I_{1}\oplus \cdots \oplus I_{r}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Thus a finitely generated torsionfree module of rank $n>0$ can be expressed as $R^{n-1}\oplus I$ , where I is a rank one projective module.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] The **Steinitz class** for P over R is the class $[I]$ of I in $Cl(R)$ : it is uniquely determined.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] Then $K_{0}(R)\cong \mathbb {Z} \oplus Cl(R)$ , where $K_{0}(R)$ is the Grothendieck group of the commutative monoid of finitely generated projective R modules.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] These results were established by Ernst Steinitz in 1912.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] An additional consequence of this structure, which is not implicit in the preceding theorem, is that if the two projective modules over a Dedekind domain have the same class in the Grothendieck group, then they are in fact abstractly isomorphic.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] There exist integral domains R that are locally but not globally Dedekind: the localization of R at each maximal ideal is a Dedekind ring (equivalently, a DVR) but R itself is not Dedekind.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] As mentioned above, such a ring cannot be Noetherian.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] It seems that the first examples of such rings were constructed by N.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dedekind-domain] In the literature such rings are sometimes called "proper almost Dedekind rings".
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] In mathematics, **Dirichlet's unit theorem** is a basic result in algebraic number theory due to Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] It determines the rank of the group of units in the ring *O**K* of algebraic integers of a number field K.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The **regulator** is a positive real number that determines how "dense" the units are.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] where *r*1 is the *number of real embeddings* and *r*2 the *number of conjugate pairs of complex embeddings* of K.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Note that if K is Galois over $\mathbb {Q}$ then either *r*1 = 0 or *r*2 = 0.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] As an example, if K is a quadratic field, the rank is 1 if it is a real quadratic field, and 0 if an imaginary quadratic field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The theory for real quadratic fields is essentially the theory of Pell's equation.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The rank is positive for all number fields besides $\mathbb {Q}$ and imaginary quadratic fields, which have rank 0.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The 'size' of the units is measured in general by a determinant called the regulator.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] In principle a basis for the units can be effectively computed; in practice the calculations are quite involved when n is large.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The torsion in the group of units is the set of all roots of unity of K, which form a finite cyclic group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] For a number field with at least one real embedding the torsion must therefore be only {1,−1}.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] There are number fields, for example most imaginary quadratic fields, having no real embeddings which also have {1,−1} for the torsion of its unit group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Totally real fields are special with respect to units.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] If *L*/*K* is a finite extension of number fields with degree greater than 1 and the units groups for the integers of L and K have the same rank then K is totally real and L is a totally complex quadratic extension.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The theorem not only applies to the maximal order OK but to any order *O* ⊂ *O*K.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] There is a generalisation of the unit theorem by Helmut Hasse (and later Claude Chevalley) to describe the structure of the group of *S-units*, determining the rank of the unit group in localizations of rings of integers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Also, the Galois module structure of $\mathbb {Q} \oplus O_{K,S}\otimes _{\mathbb {Z} }\mathbb {Q}$ has been determined.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Suppose that *K* is a number field and $u_{1},\dots ,u_{r}$ are a set of generators for the unit group of *K* modulo roots of unity.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] There will be *r* + 1 Archimedean places of *K*, either real or complex.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] For $u\in K$ , write $u^{(1)},\dots ,u^{(r+1)}$ for the different embeddings into $\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {C}$ and set *N**j* to 1 or 2 if the corresponding embedding is real or complex respectively.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Then the *r* × (*r* + 1) matrix $\left(N_{j}\log \left|u_{i}^{(j)}\right|\right)_{i=1,\dots ,r,\;j=1,\dots ,r+1}$ has the property that the sum of any row is zero (because all units have norm 1, and the log of the norm is the sum of the entries in a row).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] This implies that the absolute value R of the determinant of the submatrix formed by deleting one column is independent of the column.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The number R is called the **regulator** of the algebraic number field (it does not depend on the choice of generators *u**i*).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] It measures the "density" of the units: if the regulator is small, this means that there are "lots" of units.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The regulator has the following geometric interpretation.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The map taking a unit u to the vector with entries ${\textstyle N_{j}\log \left|u^{(j)}\right|}$ has an image in the r-dimensional subspace of $\mathbb {R} ^{r+1}$ consisting of all vectors whose entries have sum 0, and by Dirichlet's unit theorem the image is a lattice in this subspace.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The volume of a fundamental domain of this lattice is $R{\sqrt {r+1}}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The regulator of an algebraic number field of degree greater than 2 is usually quite cumbersome to calculate, though there are now computer algebra packages that can do it in many cases.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] It is usually much easier to calculate the product *hR* of the class number h and the regulator using the class number formula, and the main difficulty in calculating the class number of an algebraic number field is usually the calculation of the regulator.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] A 'higher' regulator refers to a construction for a function on an algebraic K-group with index *n* > 1 that plays the same role as the classical regulator does for the group of units, which is a group *K*1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] A theory of such regulators has been in development, with work of Armand Borel and others.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Such higher regulators play a role, for example, in the Beilinson conjectures, and are expected to occur in evaluations of certain L-functions at integer values of the argument.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The formulation of Stark's conjectures led Harold Stark to define what is now called the **Stark regulator**, similar to the classical regulator as a determinant of logarithms of units, attached to any Artin representation.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Let K be a number field and for each prime P of K above some fixed rational prime p, let *U**P* denote the local units at P and let *U*1,*P* denote the subgroup of principal units in *U**P*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Then let *E*1 denote the set of global units ε that map to *U*1 via the diagonal embedding of the global units in E.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] Since *E*1 is a finite-index subgroup of the global units, it is an abelian group of rank *r*1 + *r*2 − 1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] The **p-adic regulator** is the determinant of the matrix formed by the p-adic logarithms of the generators of this group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/dirichlet-s-unit-theorem] *Leopoldt's conjecture* states that this determinant is non-zero.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] In mathematics, the **ideal class group** (or **class group**) of an algebraic number field K is the quotient group $J_{K}/P_{K}$ where $J_{K}$ is the group of fractional ideals of the ring of integers of K , and $P_{K}$ is its subgroup of principal ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The class group is a measure of the extent to which unique factorization fails in the ring of integers of K .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The order of the group, which is finite, is called the **class number** of K .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The theory extends to Dedekind domains and their fields of fractions, for which the multiplicative properties are intimately tied to the structure of the class group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] For example, the class group of a Dedekind domain is trivial if and only if the ring is a unique factorization domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Ideal class groups (or, rather, what were effectively ideal class groups) were studied some time before the idea of an ideal was formulated.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] These groups appeared in the theory of quadratic forms: in the case of binary integral quadratic forms, as put into something like a final form by Carl Friedrich Gauss, a composition law was defined on certain equivalence classes of forms.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] This gave a finite abelian group, as was recognised at the time.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Later Ernst Kummer was working towards a theory of cyclotomic fields.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Out of Kummer's work for the first time came a study of the obstruction to the factorization.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] We now recognise this as part of the ideal class group: in fact Kummer had isolated the p -torsion in that group for the field of p -roots of unity, for any prime number p , as the reason for the failure of the standard method of attack on the Fermat problem (see regular prime).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Somewhat later again Richard Dedekind formulated the concept of an ideal, Kummer having worked in a different way.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] At this point the existing examples could be unified.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The size of the ideal class group can be considered as a measure for the deviation of a ring from being a principal ideal domain; a ring is a principal ideal domain if and only if it has a trivial ideal class group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] If R is an integral domain, define a relation $\sim$ on nonzero fractional ideals of R by $I\sim J$ whenever there exist nonzero elements a and b of R such that $(a)I=(b)J$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] It is easily shown that this is an equivalence relation.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The equivalence classes are called the *ideal classes* of R .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Ideal classes can be multiplied: if $[I]$ denotes the equivalence class of the ideal I , then the multiplication $[I][J]=[IJ]$ is well-defined and commutative.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The principal ideals form the ideal class $[R]$ which serves as an identity element for this multiplication.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Thus a class $[I]$ has an inverse $[J]$ if and only if there is an ideal J such that $IJ$ is a principal ideal.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] In general, such a J may not exist and consequently the set of ideal classes of R may only be a monoid.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] However, if R is the ring of algebraic integers in an algebraic number field, or more generally a Dedekind domain, the multiplication defined above turns the set of fractional ideal classes into an abelian group, the **ideal class group** of R .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The group property of existence of inverse elements follows easily from the fact that, in a Dedekind domain, every non-zero ideal (except R ) is a product of prime ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The ideal class group is trivial (i.e. has only one element) if and only if all ideals of R are principal.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] In this sense, the ideal class group measures how far R is from being a principal ideal domain, and hence from satisfying unique prime factorization (Dedekind domains are unique factorization domains if and only if they are principal ideal domains).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The number of ideal classes—the **class number** of R —may be infinite in general.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] In fact, every abelian group is isomorphic to the ideal class group of some Dedekind domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] But if R is a ring of algebraic integers, then the class number is always *finite*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] This is one of the main results of classical algebraic number theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Computation of the class group is hard, in general; it can be done by hand for the ring of integers in an algebraic number field of small discriminant, using Minkowski's bound.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] This result gives a bound, depending on the ring, such that every ideal class contains an ideal norm less than the bound.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] In general the bound is not sharp enough to make the calculation practical for fields with large discriminant, but computers are well suited to the task.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Higher K -groups can also be employed and interpreted arithmetically in connection to rings of integers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] It was remarked above that the ideal class group provides part of the answer to the question of how much ideals in a Dedekind domain behave like elements.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The other part of the answer is provided by the group of units of the Dedekind domain, since passage from principal ideals to their generators requires the use of units (and this is the rest of the reason for introducing the concept of fractional ideal, as well).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Define a map from $K^{\times }$ to the set of all nonzero fractional ideals of R by sending every element to the fractional ideal it generates.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] This is a group homomorphism; its kernel is the group of units of R , and its cokernel is the ideal class group of R .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The failure of these groups to be trivial is a measure of the failure of the map to be an isomorphism: that is the failure of ideals to act like ring elements, that is to say, like numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] If d is a square-free integer (a product of distinct primes) other than 1, then $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {d}})$ is a quadratic extension of $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] This result was first conjectured by Gauss and proven by Kurt Heegner, although Heegner's proof was not believed until Harold Stark gave a later proof in 1967 (see Stark–Heegner theorem).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] This is a special case of the famous class number problem.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] If, on the other hand, $d>0$ , then it is unknown whether there are infinitely many fields $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {d}})$ with class number 1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Computational results indicate that there are a great many such fields.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] However, it is not even known if there are infinitely many number fields with class number 1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] For $d<0$ , the ideal class group of $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {d}})$ is isomorphic to the class group of integral binary quadratic forms of discriminant equal to the discriminant of $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {d}})$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] For $d>0$ , the ideal class group may be half the size since the class group of integral binary quadratic forms is isomorphic to the narrow class group of $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {d}})$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] For real quadratic integer rings, the class number is given in OEIS A003649; for the imaginary case, they are given in OEIS A000924.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] The quadratic integer ring $R=\mathbb {Z} [{\sqrt {-5}}]$ is the ring of integers of $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {-5}})$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] It does not possess unique factorization; in fact the class group of R is cyclic of order 2.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] is not principal, which can be proved by contradiction as follows: R has a multiplicative norm function defined by $N(a+b{\sqrt {-5}})=a^{2}+5b^{2}$ , which satisfies $N(u)=1$ if and only if u is a unit in R .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Firstly, $J\neq R$ , because the quotient ring of R modulo the ideal $(1+{\sqrt {-5}})$ is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} /6\mathbb {Z}$ , so that the quotient ring of R modulo J is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} /3\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Now if $J=(a)$ were principal (that is, generated by an element a of R ), then a would divide both 2 and $1+{\sqrt {-5}}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] If $N(a)=1$ then a is a unit and so $J=R$ , a contradiction.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] But $N(a)$ cannot be 2 either, because R has no elements of norm 2, because the Diophantine equation $b^{2}+5c^{2}=2$ has no solutions in integers, as it has no solutions modulo 5.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] One also computes that $J^{2}=(2)$ , which is principal, so the class of J in the ideal class group has order two.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Showing that there aren't any other ideal classes requires more effort.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Class field theory is a branch of algebraic number theory which seeks to classify all the abelian extensions of a given algebraic number field, meaning Galois extensions with abelian Galois group.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] A particularly beautiful example is found in the Hilbert class field of a number field, which can be defined as the maximal unramified abelian extension of such a field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ideal-class-group] Neither property is particularly easy to prove.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] In mathematics, **Minkowski's theorem** is the statement that every convex set in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ which is symmetric with respect to the origin and which has volume greater than $2^{n}$ contains a non-zero integer point (meaning a point in $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ that is not the origin).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] The theorem was proved by Hermann Minkowski in 1889 and became the foundation of the branch of number theory called the geometry of numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] It can be extended from the integers to any lattice L and to any symmetric convex set with volume greater than $2^{n}d(L)$ , where $d(L)$ denotes the covolume of the lattice (the absolute value of the determinant of any of its bases).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Suppose that *L* is a lattice of determinant d(*L*) in the *n*-dimensional real vector space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and *S* is a convex subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ that is symmetric with respect to the origin, meaning that if *x* is in *S* then −*x* is also in *S*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Minkowski's theorem states that if the volume of *S* is strictly greater than 2*n* d(*L*), then *S* must contain at least one lattice point other than the origin.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] The simplest example of a lattice is the integer lattice $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ of all points with integer coefficients; its determinant is 1.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] For *n* = 2, the theorem claims that a convex figure in the Euclidean plane symmetric about the origin and with area greater than 4 encloses at least one lattice point in addition to the origin.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] The area bound is sharp: if *S* is the interior of the square with vertices (±1, ±1) then *S* is symmetric and convex, and has area 4, but the only lattice point it contains is the origin.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] This example, showing that the bound of the theorem is sharp, generalizes to hypercubes in every dimension *n*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Intuitively, this map cuts the plane into 2 by 2 squares, then stacks the squares on top of each other.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Clearly *f* (*S*) has area less than or equal to 4, because this set lies within a 2 by 2 square.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Assume for a contradiction that *f* could be injective, which means the pieces of *S* cut out by the squares stack up in a non-overlapping way.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Because *f* is locally area-preserving, this non-overlapping property would make it area-preserving for all of *S*, so the area of *f* (*S*) would be the same as that of *S*, which is greater than 4.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] That is not the case, so the assumption must be false: *f* is not injective, meaning that there exist at least two distinct points *p*1, *p*2 in *S* that are mapped by *f* to the same point: *f* (*p*1) = *f* (*p*2).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Because of the way *f* was defined, the only way that *f* (*p*1) can equal *f* (*p*2) is for *p*2 to equal *p*1 + (2*i*, 2*j*) for some integers *i* and *j*, not both zero.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] That is, the coordinates of the two points differ by two even integers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Since *S* is symmetric about the origin, −*p*1 is also a point in *S*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Since *S* is convex, the line segment between −*p*1 and *p*2 lies entirely in *S*, and in particular the midpoint of that segment lies in *S*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] This point (*i*, *j*) is an integer point, and is not the origin since *i* and *j* are not both zero.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Therefore, *S* contains a nonzero integer point.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Minkowski's theorem gives an upper bound for the length of the shortest nonzero vector.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] This result has applications in lattice cryptography and number theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] If ${\textstyle (2l)^{n}>2^{n}|d(L)|}$ , then ${\textstyle C}$ contains a non-zero lattice point, which is a contradiction.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] The difficult implication in Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares can be proven using Minkowski's bound on the shortest vector.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Consider the lattice ${\textstyle L}$ defined by the vectors ${\textstyle (1,j),(0,p)}$ , and let ${\textstyle B}$ denote the associated matrix.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] The determinant of this lattice is ${\textstyle p}$ , whence Minkowski's bound tells us that there is a nonzero ${\textstyle x=(x_{1},x_{2})\in \mathbb {Z} ^{2}}$ with ${\textstyle 0<\|Bx\|_{2}^{2}<2p}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Minkowski's theorem is also useful to prove Lagrange's four-square theorem, which states that every natural number can be written as the sum of the squares of four natural numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] Minkowski's theorem can be used to prove Dirichlet's theorem on simultaneous rational approximation.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] The complexity of finding the point guaranteed by Minkowski's theorem, or the closely related Blichfeldt's theorem, have been studied from the perspective of TFNP search problems.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] In particular, it is known that a computational analogue of Blichfeldt's theorem, a corollary of the proof of Minkowski's theorem, is PPP-complete.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/minkowski-s-theorem] It is also known that the computational analogue of Minkowski's theorem is in the class PPP, and it was conjectured to be PPP-complete.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In geometry, **ramification** is 'branching out', in the way that the square root function, for complex numbers, can be seen to have two *branches* differing in sign.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The term is also used from the opposite perspective (branches coming together) as when a covering map degenerates at a point of a space, with some collapsing of the fibers of the mapping.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] Ramification is the main object of study in **ramification theory**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In complex analysis, the basic model can be taken as the *z* → *z**n* mapping in the complex plane, near *z* = 0.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] This is the standard local picture in Riemann surface theory, of ramification of order *n*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] It occurs for example in the Riemann–Hurwitz formula for the effect of mappings on the genus.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In a covering map the Euler–Poincaré characteristic should multiply by the number of sheets; ramification can therefore be detected by some dropping from that.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In geometric terms, ramification is something that happens in *codimension two* (like knot theory, and monodromy); since *real* codimension two is *complex* codimension one, the local complex example sets the pattern for higher-dimensional complex manifolds.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In complex analysis, sheets can't simply fold over along a line (one variable), or codimension one subspace in the general case.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The ramification set (branch locus on the base, double point set above) will be two real dimensions lower than the ambient manifold, and so will not separate it into two 'sides', locally―there will be paths that trace round the branch locus, just as in the example.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In algebraic geometry over any field, by analogy, it also happens in algebraic codimension one.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] Ramification in algebraic number theory means a prime ideal factoring in an extension so as to give some repeated prime ideal factors.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] Namely, let ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ be the ring of integers of an algebraic number field K , and ${\mathfrak {p}}$ a prime ideal of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] For a field extension $L/K$ we can consider the ring of integers ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ (which is the integral closure of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ in L ), and the ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}{\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ of ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] where the ${\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ are distinct prime ideals of ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] Then ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is said to **ramify** in L if $e_{i}>1$ for some i ; otherwise it is **unramified**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In other words, ${\mathfrak {p}}$ ramifies in L if the **ramification index** $e_{i}$ is greater than one for some ${\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] An equivalent condition is that ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}/{\mathfrak {p}}{\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ has a non-zero nilpotent element: it is not a product of finite fields.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The analogy with the Riemann surface case was already pointed out by Richard Dedekind and Heinrich M.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The ramification is encoded in K by the relative discriminant and in L by the relative different.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The former is an ideal of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ and is divisible by ${\mathfrak {p}}$ if and only if some ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ of ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ dividing ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is ramified.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The latter is an ideal of ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ and is divisible by the prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ of ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ precisely when ${\mathfrak {p}}_{i}$ is ramified.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The ramification is **tame** when the ramification indices $e_{i}$ are all relatively prime to the residue characteristic *p* of ${\mathfrak {p}}$ , otherwise **wild**.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] This condition is important in Galois module theory.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] A finite generically étale extension $B/A$ of Dedekind domains is tame if and only if the trace $\operatorname {Tr} :B\to A$ is surjective.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The more detailed analysis of ramification in number fields can be carried out using extensions of the p-adic numbers, because it is a *local* question.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In that case a quantitative measure of ramification is defined for Galois extensions, basically by asking how far the Galois group moves field elements with respect to the metric.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] A sequence of ramification groups is defined, reifying (amongst other things) *wild* (non-tame) ramification.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] This goes beyond the geometric analogue.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] In valuation theory, the ramification theory of valuations studies the set of extensions of a valuation of a field *K* to an extension field of *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] This generalizes the notions in algebraic number theory, local fields, and Dedekind domains.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] There is also corresponding notion of unramified morphism in algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] Let $f:X\to Y$ be a morphism of schemes.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] The support of the quasicoherent sheaf $\Omega _{X/Y}$ is called the **ramification locus** of f and the image of the ramification locus, $f\left(\operatorname {Supp} \Omega _{X/Y}\right)$ , is called the **branch locus** of f .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ramification-mathematics] If $\Omega _{X/Y}=0$ we say that f is **formally unramified** and if f is also of locally finite presentation we say that f is **unramified** (see Vakil 2017).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] In mathematics, the **ring of integers** of an algebraic number field K (also sometimes called the **number ring** corresponding to number field *K*) is the ring of all algebraic integers contained in K .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] An algebraic integer is a root of a monic polynomial with integer coefficients: $x^{n}+c_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots +c_{0}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] This ring is often denoted by $O_{K}$ or ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] Since any integer belongs to K and is an integral element of K , the ring $\mathbb {Z}$ is always a subring of $O_{K}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] The ring of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ is the simplest possible ring of integers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] Namely, $\mathbb {Z} =O_{\mathbb {Q} }$ where $\mathbb {Q}$ is the field of rational numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] And indeed, in algebraic number theory the elements of $\mathbb {Z}$ are often called the "rational integers" because of this.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] The next simplest example is the ring of Gaussian integers $\mathbb {Z} [i]$ , consisting of complex numbers whose real and imaginary parts are integers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] It is the ring of integers in the number field $\mathbb {Q} (i)$ of Gaussian rationals, consisting of complex numbers whose real and imaginary parts are rational numbers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] Like the rational integers, $\mathbb {Z} [i]$ is a Euclidean domain.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] The ring of integers of an algebraic number field is the unique maximal order in the field.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] The ring of integers O*K* is a finitely-generated $\mathbb {Z}$ -module.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] The rank n of O*K* as a free $\mathbb {Z}$ -module is equal to the degree of K over $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] A useful tool for computing the integral closure of the ring of integers in an algebraic field $K/\mathbb {Q}$ is the discriminant.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] Then, ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ is a submodule of the $\mathbb {Z}$ -module spanned by $\alpha _{1}/d,\ldots ,\alpha _{n}/d$ . pg.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] 33 In fact, if *d* is square-free, then $\alpha _{1},\ldots ,\alpha _{n}$ forms an integral basis for ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ . pg.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] If p is a prime, *ζ* is a pth root of unity and $K=\mathbb {Q} (\zeta )$ is the corresponding cyclotomic field, then an integral basis of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}=\mathbb {Z} [\zeta ]$ is given by (1, *ζ*, *ζ* 2, ..., *ζ* *p*−2).
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] This can be found by computing the minimal polynomial of an arbitrary element $a+b{\sqrt {d}}\in \mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {d}})$ where $a,b\in \mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] A ring of integers is always a Dedekind domain, and so has unique factorization of ideals into prime ideals.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] The units of a ring of integers *O**K* is a finitely generated abelian group by Dirichlet's unit theorem.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] The torsion subgroup consists of the roots of unity of *K*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] A set of torsion-free generators is called a set of *fundamental units*.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] One defines the ring of integers of a non-archimedean local field *F* as the set of all elements of *F* with absolute value ≤ 1; this is a ring because of the strong triangle inequality.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] If *F* is the completion of an algebraic number field, its ring of integers is the completion of the latter's ring of integers.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] The ring of integers of an algebraic number field may be characterised as the elements which are integers in every non-archimedean completion.
[src:algebraic-number-theory/ring-of-integers] For example, the p-adic integers $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ are the ring of integers of the p-adic numbers $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ .
